[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] The security of FE requires that any information an adversary learns from an encryption of x is revealed by $f(x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] Formally, this is defined by simulation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] Functional encryption generalizes several existing primitives including Identity-based encryption (IBE) and attribute-based encryption (ABE).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] In the IBE case, define $F(k,x)$ to be equal to x when k corresponds to an identity that is allowed to decrypt, and $\perp$ otherwise.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] Similarly, in the ABE case, define $F(k,x)=x$ when k encodes attributes with permission to decrypt and $\perp$ otherwise.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] Functional encryption was proposed by Amit Sahai and Brent Waters in 2005 and formalized by Dan Boneh, Amit Sahai and Brent Waters in 2010.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] Until recently, however, most instantiations of Functional Encryption supported only limited function classes such as boolean formulae.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/functional-encryption] In 2012, several researchers developed Functional Encryption schemes that support arbitrary functions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] As an example of a practical application of homomorphic encryption: encrypted photographs can be scanned for points of interest, without revealing the contents of a photo.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] However, observation of side-channels can see a photograph being sent to a point-of-interest lookup service, revealing the fact that photographs were taken.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Thus, homomorphic encryption eliminates the need for processing data in the clear, thereby preventing attacks that would enable an attacker to access that data while it is being processed, using privilege escalation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] For sensitive data, such as healthcare information, homomorphic encryption can be used to enable new services by removing privacy barriers inhibiting data sharing or increasing security to existing services.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] For example, predictive analytics in healthcare can be hard to apply via a third-party service provider due to medical data privacy concerns.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] But if the predictive-analytics service provider could operate on encrypted data instead, without having the decryption keys, these privacy concerns are diminished.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Moreover, even if the service provider's system is compromised, the data would remain secure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption is a form of encryption with an additional evaluation capability for computing over encrypted data without access to the secret key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The result of such a computation remains encrypted.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption can be viewed as an extension of public-key cryptography, because ciphertexts can be manipulated algebraically to produce an encrypted result corresponding to operations on the underlying plaintexts.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] *Homomorphic* refers to homomorphism in algebra: the encryption and decryption functions can be thought of as homomorphisms between plaintext and ciphertext spaces.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption includes multiple types of encryption schemes that can perform different classes of computations over encrypted data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The computations are represented as either Boolean or arithmetic circuits.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] For the majority of homomorphic encryption schemes, the multiplicative depth of circuits is the main practical limitation in performing computations over encrypted data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes are inherently malleable.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] In terms of malleability, homomorphic encryption schemes have weaker security properties than non-homomorphic schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] A cryptosystem that supports *arbitrary computation* on ciphertexts is known as fully homomorphic encryption (FHE).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Such a scheme enables the construction of programs for any desirable functionality, which can be run on encrypted inputs to produce an encryption of the result.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Since such a program need never decrypt its inputs, it can be run by an untrusted party without revealing its inputs and internal state.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Fully homomorphic cryptosystems have great practical implications in the outsourcing of private computations, for instance, in the context of cloud computing.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes have been developed using different approaches.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Specifically, fully homomorphic encryption schemes are often grouped into generations corresponding to the underlying approach.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The problem of constructing a fully homomorphic encryption scheme was first proposed in 1978, within a year of publishing of the RSA scheme.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] For more than 30 years, it was unclear whether a solution existed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Craig Gentry, using lattice-based cryptography, described the first plausible construction for a fully homomorphic encryption scheme in 2009.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's scheme supports both addition and multiplication operations on ciphertexts, from which it is possible to construct circuits for performing arbitrary computation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry then shows how to slightly modify this scheme to make it *bootstrappable*, i.e., capable of evaluating its own decryption circuit and then at least one more operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Finally, he shows that any bootstrappable somewhat homomorphic encryption scheme can be converted into a fully homomorphic encryption through a recursive self-embedding.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] For Gentry's "noisy" scheme, the bootstrapping procedure effectively "refreshes" the ciphertext by applying to it the decryption procedure homomorphically, thereby obtaining a new ciphertext that encrypts the same value as before but has lower noise.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] By "refreshing" the ciphertext periodically whenever the noise grows too large, it is possible to compute an arbitrary number of additions and multiplications without increasing the noise too much.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry based the security of his scheme on the assumed hardness of two problems: certain worst-case problems over ideal lattices, and the sparse (or low-weight) subset sum problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's Ph.D. thesis provides additional details.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The Gentry-Halevi implementation of Gentry's original cryptosystem reported a timing of about 30 minutes per basic bit operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Extensive design and implementation work in subsequent years have improved upon these early implementations by many orders of magnitude runtime performance.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] In 2010, Marten van Dijk, Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi and Vinod Vaikuntanathan presented a second fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which uses many of the tools of Gentry's construction, but which does not require ideal lattices.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Instead, they show that the somewhat homomorphic component of Gentry's ideal lattice-based scheme can be replaced with a very simple somewhat homomorphic scheme that uses integers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The scheme is therefore conceptually simpler than Gentry's ideal lattice scheme, but has similar properties with regards to homomorphic operations and efficiency.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The somewhat homomorphic component in the work of Van Dijk et al. is similar to an encryption scheme proposed by Levieil and Naccache in 2008, and also to one that was proposed by Bram Cohen in 1998.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Cohen's method is not even additively homomorphic, however.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The Levieil–Naccache scheme supports only additions, but it can be modified to also support a small number of multiplications.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Many refinements and optimizations of the scheme of Van Dijk et al. were proposed in a sequence of works by Jean-Sébastien Coron, Tancrède Lepoint, Avradip Mandal, David Naccache, and Mehdi Tibouchi.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Some of these works included also implementations of the resulting schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The homomorphic cryptosystems of this generation are derived from techniques that were developed starting in 2011–2012 by Zvika Brakerski, Craig Gentry, Vinod Vaikuntanathan, and others.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] These innovations led to the development of much more efficient somewhat and fully homomorphic cryptosystems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The security of most of these schemes is based on the hardness of the (Ring) Learning With Errors (RLWE) problem, except for the LTV and BLLN schemes that rely on an *overstretched* variant of the NTRU computational problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] This NTRU variant was subsequently shown vulnerable to subfield lattice attacks, which is why these two schemes are no longer used in practice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] All the second-generation cryptosystems still follow the basic blueprint of Gentry's original construction, namely they first construct a somewhat homomorphic cryptosystem and then convert it to a fully homomorphic cryptosystem using bootstrapping.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] A distinguishing characteristic of the second-generation cryptosystems is that they all feature a much slower growth of the noise during the homomorphic computations.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Additional optimizations by Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi, and Nigel Smart resulted in cryptosystems with nearly optimal asymptotic complexity: Performing T operations on data encrypted with security parameter k has complexity of only $T\cdot \mathrm {polylog} (k)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] These optimizations build on the Smart-Vercauteren techniques that enable packing of many plaintext values in a single ciphertext and operating on all these plaintext values in a SIMD fashion.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Many of the advances in these second-generation cryptosystems were also ported to the cryptosystem over the integers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Another distinguishing feature of second-generation schemes is that they are efficient enough for many applications even without invoking bootstrapping, instead operating in the leveled FHE mode.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] In 2013, Craig Gentry, Amit Sahai, and Brent Waters (GSW) proposed a new technique for building FHE schemes that avoids an expensive "relinearization" step in homomorphic multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Zvika Brakerski and Vinod Vaikuntanathan observed that for certain types of circuits, the GSW cryptosystem features an even slower growth rate of noise, and hence better efficiency and stronger security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Jacob Alperin-Sheriff and Chris Peikert then described a very efficient bootstrapping technique based on this observation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] These techniques were further improved to develop efficient ring variants of the GSW cryptosystem: FHEW (2014) and TFHE (2016).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The FHEW scheme was the first to show that by refreshing the ciphertexts after every single operation, it is possible to reduce the bootstrapping time to a fraction of a second.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] FHEW introduced a new method to compute Boolean gates on encrypted data that greatly simplifies bootstrapping and implemented a variant of the bootstrapping procedure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The efficiency of FHEW was further improved by the TFHE scheme, which implements a ring variant of the bootstrapping procedure using a method similar to the one in FHEW.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] In 2016, Jung Hee Cheon, Andrey Kim, Miran Kim, and Yongsoo Song (CKKS) proposed an approximate homomorphic encryption scheme that supports a special kind of fixed-point arithmetic that is commonly referred to as block floating point arithmetic.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The CKKS scheme includes an efficient rescaling operation that scales down an encrypted message after a multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] For comparison, such rescaling requires bootstrapping in the BGV and BFV schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The rescaling operation makes CKKS scheme the most efficient method for evaluating polynomial approximations, and is the preferred approach for implementing privacy-preserving machine learning applications.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The scheme introduces several approximation errors, both nondeterministic and deterministic, that require special handling in practice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] A 2020 article by Baiyu Li and Daniele Micciancio discusses passive attacks against CKKS, suggesting that the standard IND-CPA definition may not be sufficient in scenarios where decryption results are shared.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The authors apply the attack to four modern homomorphic encryption libraries (HEAAN, SEAL, HElib and PALISADE) and report that it is possible to recover the secret key from decryption results in several parameter configurations.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The authors also propose mitigation strategies for these attacks, and include a Responsible Disclosure in the paper suggesting that the homomorphic encryption libraries already implemented mitigations for the attacks before the article became publicly available.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Further information on the mitigation strategies implemented in the homomorphic encryption libraries has also been published.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] In the following examples, the notation ${\mathcal {E}}(x)$ is used to denote the encryption of the message x .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] where $\oplus$ denotes addition modulo 2, (i.e., exclusive-or).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] There are several open-source implementations of partially, somewhat and fully homomorphic encryption schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Second-generation and fourth-generation FHE scheme implementations typically operate in the leveled FHE mode (though bootstrapping is still available in some libraries) and support efficient SIMD-like packing of data; they are typically used to compute on encrypted integers or real/complex numbers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Third-generation FHE scheme implementations often bootstrap after each operation but have limited support for packing; they were initially used to compute Boolean circuits over encrypted bits, but have been extended to support integer arithmetics and univariate function evaluation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] The choice of using a second-generation vs. third-generation vs fourth-generation scheme depends on the input data types and the desired computation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] General-purpose lattice cryptography library.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] TFHE-extended compiler with a Python Frontend.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] Verifiable encrypted computations based on Rinocchio ZKP and BGV homomorphic Encryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/homomorphic-encryption] In 2017, researchers from IBM, Microsoft, Intel, the NIST, and others formed the open Homomorphic Encryption Standardization Consortium, which maintains a community security Homomorphic Encryption Standard.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] In 2024 NIST announced the Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Standard for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] She then showed a cryptographic hash function whose security is equivalent to the computational hardness of SIS.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] In 1998, Jeffrey Hoffstein, Jill Pipher, and Joseph H.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Silverman introduced a lattice-based public-key encryption scheme, known as NTRU.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] However, their scheme is not known to be at least as hard as solving a worst-case lattice problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] The first lattice-based public-key encryption scheme whose security was proven under worst-case hardness assumptions was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005, together with the learning with errors problem (LWE).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Since then, much follow-up work has focused on improving Regev's security proof and improving the efficiency of the original scheme.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Much more work has been devoted to constructing additional cryptographic primitives based on LWE and related problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] For example, in 2009, Craig Gentry introduced the first fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which was based on a lattice problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] In linear algebra, a lattice $L\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the set of all integer linear combinations of vectors from a basis $\{\mathbf {b} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {b} _{n}\}$ of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] In other words, $L={\Big \{}\sum a_{i}\mathbf {b} _{i}:a_{i}\in \mathbb {Z} {\Big \}}.$ For example, $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ is a lattice, generated by the standard basis for $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Crucially, the basis for a lattice is not unique.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] The most important lattice-based computational problem is the shortest vector problem (SVP or sometimes GapSVP), which asks for an approximate minimal Euclidean length of a non-zero lattice vector.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] This problem is thought to be hard to solve efficiently, even with approximation factors that are polynomial in n , and even with a quantum computer.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Many (though not all) lattice-based cryptographic constructions are known to be secure if SVP is in fact hard in this regime.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] This section presents selected lattice-based schemes, grouped by primitive.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] This section lists a selection of lattice-based schemes for the purpose of digital signatures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] CRYSTALS-Dilithium or simply Dilithium is built upon module-LWE and module-SIS.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was selected by the NIST as the basis for a digital signature standard.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] According to a message from Ray Perlner, writing on behalf of the NIST PQC team, the NIST module-LWE signing standard is to be based on version 3.1 of the Dilithium specification.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] NIST's changes on Dilithium 3.1 intend to support additional randomness in signing (hedged signing) and other improvements.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was one of the two digital signature schemes initially chosen by the NIST in their post-quantum cryptography process, the other one being SPHINCS+, which is not based on lattices but on hashes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2023, NIST published FIPS 204 (Initial Public Draft), and started calling Dilithium "Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Algorithm" (ML-DSA).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] As of October 2023, ML-DSA was being implemented as a part of Libgcrypt, according to Falko Strenzke.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2024, NIST officially standardized CRYSTALS-Dilithium under the name ML-DSA, establishing it as the primary standard (FIPS 204) for quantum-resistant digital signatures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Lattice-based cryptographic constructions hold a great promise for public-key post-quantum cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Indeed, the main alternative forms of public-key cryptography are schemes based on the hardness of factoring and related problems and schemes based on the hardness of the discrete logarithm and related problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] However, both factoring and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be solvable in polynomial time on a quantum computer.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Furthermore, algorithms for factorization tend to yield algorithms for discrete logarithm, and conversely.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] This further motivates the study of constructions based on alternative assumptions, such as the hardness of lattice problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Many lattice-based cryptographic schemes are known to be secure assuming the *worst-case* hardness of certain lattice problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] I.e., if there exists an algorithm that can efficiently break the cryptographic scheme with non-negligible probability, then there exists an efficient algorithm that solves a certain lattice problem on any input.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] However, for the practical lattice-based constructions (such as schemes based on NTRU and even schemes based on LWE with efficient parameters), meaningful reduction-based guarantees of security are not known.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] Some authors who have investigated concrete security for lattice-based cryptosystems have found that the provable security results for such systems do not provide any meaningful concrete security for practical values of the parameters.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] For many cryptographic primitives, the only known constructions are based on lattices or closely related objects.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/lattice-based-cryptography] These primitives include fully homomorphic encryption, indistinguishability obfuscation, cryptographic multilinear maps, and functional encryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In cryptography, **learning with errors** (**LWE**) is a mathematical problem that is widely used to create secure encryption algorithms.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] It is based on the idea of representing secret information as a set of equations with errors.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In other words, LWE is a way to hide the value of a secret by introducing noise to it.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In more technical terms, it refers to the computational problem of inferring a linear n -ary function f over a finite ring from given samples $y_{i}=f(\mathbf {x} _{i})$ some of which may be erroneous.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The LWE problem is conjectured to be hard to solve, and thus to be useful in cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] More precisely, the LWE problem is defined as follows.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Let $\mathbb {Z} _{q}$ denote the ring of integers modulo q and let $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ denote the set of n -vectors over $\mathbb {Z} _{q}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Furthermore, the deviation from the equality is according to some known noise model.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The problem calls for finding the function f , or some close approximation thereof, with high probability.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The LWE problem was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005 (who won the 2018 Gödel Prize for this work); it is a generalization of the parity learning problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Regev showed that the LWE problem is as hard to solve as several worst-case lattice problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Subsequently, the LWE problem has been used as a hardness assumption to create public-key cryptosystems, such as the ring learning with errors key exchange by Peikert.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Denote by $\mathbb {T} =\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z}$ the additive group on reals modulo one.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Let $\mathbf {s} \in \mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ be a fixed vector.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Let $\phi$ be a fixed probability distribution over $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Denote by $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\phi }$ the distribution on $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}\times \mathbb {T}$ obtained as follows.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The **learning with errors problem** $\mathrm {LWE} _{q,\phi }$ is to find $\mathbf {s} \in \mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ , given access to polynomially many samples of choice from $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\phi }$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The **LWE** problem described above is the *search* version of the problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In the *decision* version (**DLWE**), the goal is to distinguish between noisy inner products and uniformly random samples from $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}\times \mathbb {T}$ (practically, some discretized version of it).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Regev showed that the *decision* and *search* versions are equivalent when q is a prime bounded by some polynomial in n .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Intuitively, if we have a procedure for the search problem, the decision version can be solved easily: just feed the input samples for the decision problem to the solver for the search problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] If the solver returns a candidate $\mathbf {s}$ , for all i , calculate $\{\langle \mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {s} \rangle -\mathbf {b} _{i}\}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] If the samples are from an LWE distribution, then the results of this calculation will be distributed according $\chi$ , but if the samples are uniformly random, these quantities will be distributed uniformly as well.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] For the other direction, given a solver for the decision problem, the search version can be solved as follows: Recover $\mathbf {s}$ one coordinate at a time.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] To obtain the first coordinate, $\mathbf {s} _{1}$ , make a guess $k\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ , and do the following.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Choose a number $r\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ uniformly at random.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Send the transformed samples to the decision solver.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] If the guess k was correct, the transformation takes the distribution $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\chi }$ to itself, and otherwise, since q is prime, it takes it to the uniform distribution.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] So, given a polynomial-time solver for the decision problem that errs with very small probability, since q is bounded by some polynomial in n , it only takes polynomial time to guess every possible value for k and use the solver to see which one is correct.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] After obtaining $\mathbf {s} _{1}$ , we follow an analogous procedure for each other coordinate $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Namely, we transform our $\mathbf {b} _{i}$ samples the same way, and transform our $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ samples by calculating $\mathbf {a} _{i}+(0,\ldots ,r,\ldots ,0)$ , where the r is in the $j^{\text{th}}$ coordinate.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Peikert showed that this reduction, with a small modification, works for any q that is a product of distinct, small (polynomial in n ) primes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The main idea is if $q=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{t}$ , for each $q_{\ell }$ , guess and check to see if $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ is congruent to $0\mod q_{\ell }$ , and then use the Chinese remainder theorem to recover $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Regev showed the random self-reducibility of the **LWE** and **DLWE** problems for arbitrary q and $\chi$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Then there would be some distinguisher ${\mathcal {A}}$ , who, given samples $\{(\mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {b} _{i})\}$ , could tell whether they were uniformly random or from $A_{\mathbf {s} ',\chi }$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Thus, no such ${\mathcal {S}}$ can exist, meaning **LWE** and **DLWE** are (up to a polynomial factor) as hard in the average case as they are in the worst case.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Let $D_{L,r}$ denote the discrete Gaussian distribution on L of width r for a lattice L and real $r>0$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The probability of each $x\in L$ is proportional to $\rho _{r}(x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The *discrete Gaussian sampling problem* (DGS) is defined as follows: An instance of $DGS_{\phi }$ is given by an n -dimensional lattice L and a number $r\geq \phi (L)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The goal is to output a sample from $D_{L,r}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Regev shows that there is a reduction from $\operatorname {GapSVP} _{100{\sqrt {n}}\gamma (n)}$ to $DGS_{{\sqrt {n}}\gamma (n)/\lambda (L^{*})}$ for any function $\gamma (n)\geq 1$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Regev then shows that there exists an efficient quantum algorithm for $DGS_{{\sqrt {2n}}\eta _{\varepsilon }(L)/\alpha }$ given access to an oracle for $\mathrm {LWE} _{q,\Psi _{\alpha }}$ for integer q and $\alpha \in (0,1)$ such that $\alpha q>2{\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Although the proof of this assertion works for any q , for creating a cryptosystem, the modulus q has to be polynomial in n .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The **LWE** problem serves as a versatile problem used in construction of several cryptosystems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In 2005, Regev showed that the decision version of LWE is hard assuming quantum hardness of the lattice problems $\mathrm {GapSVP} _{\gamma }$ (for $\gamma$ as above) and $\mathrm {SIVP} _{t}$ with $t=O(n/\alpha )$ ).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In 2009, Peikert proved a similar result assuming only the classical hardness of the related problem $\mathrm {GapSVP} _{\zeta ,\gamma }$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The disadvantage of Peikert's result is that it bases itself on a non-standard version of an easier (when compared to SIVP) problem GapSVP.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Regev proposed a public-key cryptosystem based on the hardness of the **LWE** problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The cryptosystem as well as the proof of security and correctness are completely classical.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The system is characterized by $m,q$ and a probability distribution $\chi$ on $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The proof of correctness follows from choice of parameters and some probability analysis.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] Peikert proposed a system that is secure even against any chosen-ciphertext attack.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The idea of using LWE and Ring LWE for key exchange was proposed and filed at the University of Cincinnati in 2011 by Jintai Ding.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The idea comes from the associativity of matrix multiplications, and the errors are used to provide the security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The paper appeared in 2012 after a provisional patent application was filed in 2012.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The security of the protocol is proven based on the hardness of solving the LWE problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] In 2014, Peikert presented a key-transport scheme following the same basic idea of Ding's, where the new idea of sending an additional 1-bit signal for rounding in Ding's construction is also used.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] The "new hope" implementation selected for Google's post-quantum experiment, uses Peikert's scheme with variation in the error distribution.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/learning-with-errors] A RLWE version of the classic Feige–Fiat–Shamir Identification protocol was created and converted to a digital signature in 2011 by Lyubashevsky.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The **Paillier cryptosystem**, invented by and named after Pascal Paillier in 1999, is a probabilistic asymmetric algorithm for public key cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The problem of computing *n*-th residue classes is believed to be computationally difficult.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The decisional composite residuosity assumption is the intractability hypothesis upon which this cryptosystem is based.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The scheme is an additive homomorphic cryptosystem; this means that, given only the public key and the encryption of $m_{1}$ and $m_{2}$ , one can compute the encryption of $m_{1}+m_{2}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Compute $n=pq$ and $\lambda =\operatorname {lcm} (p-1,q-1)$ . lcm means Least Common Multiple.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] If using p,q of equivalent length, a simpler variant of the above key generation steps would be to set $g=n+1,\lambda =\varphi (n),$ and $\mu =\varphi (n)^{-1}{\bmod {n}}$ , where $\varphi (n)=(p-1)(q-1)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The simpler variant is **recommended** for implementational purposes, because in the general form the calculation time of $\mu$ can be very high with sufficiently large primes p,q.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] A notable feature of the Paillier cryptosystem is its homomorphic properties along with its non-deterministic encryption (see Electronic voting in Applications for usage).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] However, given the Paillier encryptions of two messages there is no known way to compute an encryption of the product of these messages without knowing the private key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Paillier cryptosystem exploits the fact that certain discrete logarithms can be computed easily.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The original cryptosystem as shown above does provide semantic security against chosen-plaintext attacks (IND-CPA).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The ability to successfully distinguish the challenge ciphertext essentially amounts to the ability to decide composite residuosity.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The so-called decisional composite residuosity assumption (DCRA) is believed to be intractable.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Because of the aforementioned homomorphic properties however, the system is malleable, and therefore does not enjoy the highest level of semantic security, protection against adaptive chosen-ciphertext attacks (IND-CCA2).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Usually in cryptography the notion of malleability is not seen as an "advantage," but under certain applications such as secure electronic voting and threshold cryptosystems, this property may indeed be necessary.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Paillier and Pointcheval however went on to propose an improved cryptosystem that incorporates the combined hashing of message *m* with random *r*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Similar in intent to the Cramer–Shoup cryptosystem, the hashing prevents an attacker, given only *c,* from being able to change *m* in a meaningful way.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Through this adaptation the improved scheme can be shown to be IND-CCA2 secure in the random oracle model.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Semantic security is not the only consideration.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] There are situations under which malleability may be desirable.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Secure electronic voting systems can utilize the above homomorphic properties.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Consider a simple binary ("for" or "against") vote.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Let *m* voters cast a vote of either *1* (for) or *0* (against).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Each voter encrypts their choice before casting their vote.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The election official takes the product of the *m* encrypted votes and then decrypts the result and obtains the value *n*, which is the sum of all the votes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The election official then knows that *n* people voted *for* and *m-n* people voted *against*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The role of the random *r* ensures that two equivalent votes will encrypt to the same value only with negligible likelihood, hence ensuring voter privacy.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Another feature named in paper is the notion of self-blinding.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] This is the ability to change one ciphertext into another without changing the content of its decryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] This has application to the development of ecash, an effort originally spearheaded by David Chaum.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] Imagine paying for an item online without the vendor needing to know your credit card number, and hence your identity.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The goal in both electronic cash and electronic voting, is to ensure the e-coin (likewise e-vote) is valid, while at the same time not disclosing the identity of the person with whom it is currently associated.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The Paillier cryptosystem plays a crucial role in enhancing the security of electronic auctions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] It prevents fraudulent activities such as dishonest auctioneers and collusion between bidders and auctioneers who manipulate bids.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] By ensuring the confidentiality of actual bidding values while revealing auction results, the Pailler cryptosystem successfully promotes fair practices.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/paillier-cryptosystem] The homomorphic property of Paillier cryptosystem is sometimes used to build Threshold ECDSA signature.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] In post-quantum cryptography, **ring learning with errors** (**RLWE**) is a computational problem which serves as the foundation of new cryptographic algorithms, such as NewHope, designed to protect against cryptanalysis by quantum computers and also to provide the basis for homomorphic encryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Public-key cryptography relies on construction of mathematical problems that are believed to be hard to solve if no further information is available, but are easy to solve if some information used in the problem construction is known.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Some problems of this sort that are currently used in cryptography are at risk of attack if sufficiently large quantum computers can ever be built, so resistant problems are sought.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] RLWE is more properly called *learning with errors over rings* and is simply the larger learning with errors (LWE) problem specialized to polynomial rings over finite fields.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The security of modern cryptography, in particular public-key cryptography, is based on the assumed intractability of solving certain computational problems if the size of the problem is large enough and the instance of the problem to be solved is chosen randomly.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The classic example that has been used since the 1970s is the integer factorization problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] It is believed that it is computationally intractable to factor the product of two prime numbers if those prime numbers are large enough and chosen at random.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] As of 2015 research has led to the factorization of the product of two 384-bit primes but not the product of two 512-bit primes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Integer factorization forms the basis of the widely used RSA cryptographic algorithm.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The ring learning with errors (RLWE) problem is built on the arithmetic of polynomials with coefficients from a finite field.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Polynomials can be added and multiplied in the usual fashion.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] In the RLWE context the coefficients of the polynomials and all operations involving those coefficients will be done in a finite field, typically the field ${\textstyle \mathbf {Z} /q\mathbf {Z} =\mathbf {F} _{q}}$ for a prime integer ${\textstyle q}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The set of polynomials over a finite field with the operations of addition and multiplication forms an infinite polynomial ring ( ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{q}[x]}$ ).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The RLWE context works with a finite quotient ring of this infinite ring.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The quotient ring is typically the finite quotient (factor) ring formed by reducing all of the polynomials in ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{q}[x]}$ modulo an irreducible polynomial ${\textstyle \Phi (x)}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] This finite quotient ring can be written as $\mathbf {F} _{q}[x]/\Phi (x)$ though many authors write $\mathbf {Z} _{q}[x]/\Phi (x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] If the degree of the polynomial $\Phi (x)$ is ${\textstyle n}$ , the quotient ring becomes the ring of polynomials of degree less than n modulo $\Phi (x)$ with coefficients from $F_{q}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The values ${\textstyle n}$ , ${\textstyle q}$ , together with the polynomial $\Phi (x)$ partially define the mathematical context for the RLWE problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Another concept necessary for the RLWE problem is the idea of "small" polynomials with respect to some norm.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The typical norm used in the RLWE problem is known as the infinity norm (also called the uniform norm).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The infinity norm of a polynomial is simply the largest coefficient of the polynomial when these coefficients are viewed as integers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Hence, $||a(x)||_{\infty }=b$ states that the infinity norm of the polynomial $a(x)$ is b .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Thus b is the largest coefficient of $a(x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The final concept necessary to understand the RLWE problem is the generation of random polynomials in $\mathbf {F} _{q}[x]/\Phi (x)$ and the generation of "small" polynomials .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] A random polynomial is easily generated by simply randomly sampling the n coefficients of the polynomial from $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ , where $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ is typically represented as the set $\{-(q-1)/2,...,-1,0,1,...,(q-1)/2\}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Randomly generating a "small" polynomial is done by generating the coefficients of the polynomial from $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ in a way that either guarantees small coefficients or makes them very likely.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The references describe in full detail how this can be accomplished.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] It is more complicated than uniform sampling but it allows for a proof of security of the algorithm.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The paper "Sampling from Discrete Gaussians for Lattice-Based Cryptography on a Constrained Device" by Dwarakanath and Galbraith provides an overview of this problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The RLWE problem can be stated in two different ways: a "search" version and a "decision" version.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The Search version entails finding the unknown polynomial $s(x)$ given the list of polynomial pairs $(a_{i}(x),b_{i}(x))$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The Decision version of the problem can be stated as follows.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Given a list of polynomial pairs $(a_{i}(x),b_{i}(x))$ , determine whether the $b_{i}(x)$ polynomials were constructed as $b_{i}(x)=(a_{i}(x)\cdot s(x))+e_{i}(x)$ or were generated randomly from $\mathbf {F} _{q}[x]/\Phi (x)$ with coefficients from all of $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The difficulty of this problem is parameterized by the choice of the quotient polynomial ( $\Phi (x)$ ), its degree ( n ), the field ( $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ ), and the smallness bound ( b ).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] In many RLWE based public key algorithms the private key will be a pair of small polynomials $s(x)$ and $e(x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The corresponding public key will be a pair of polynomials $a(x)$ , selected randomly from $\mathbf {F} _{q}[x]/\Phi (x)$ , and the polynomial $t(x)=(a(x)\cdot s(x))+e(x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Given $a(x)$ and $t(x)$ , it should be computationally infeasible to recover the polynomial $s(x)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The difficulty of solving the search version of RLWE problem is equivalent to finding a short vector (but not necessarily the shortest vector) in an ideal lattice formed from elements of $\mathbf {Z} [x]/\Phi (x)$ represented as integer vectors.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] This problem is commonly known as the Approximate Shortest Vector Problem (α-SVP) and it is the problem of finding a vector shorter than α times the shortest vector.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The α-SVP in regular lattices is known to be NP-hard due to work by Daniele Micciancio in 2001, although not for values of α required for a reduction to general learning with errors problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] However, there is not yet a proof to show that the difficulty of the α-SVP for ideal lattices is equivalent to the average α-SVP.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Rather we have a proof that if there are *any* α-SVP instances that are hard to solve in ideal lattices then the RLWE Problem will be hard in random instances.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Regarding the difficulty of Shortest Vector Problems in Ideal Lattices, researcher Michael Schneider writes, *"So far there is no SVP algorithm making use of the special structure of ideal lattices.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] It is widely believed that solving SVP (and all other lattice problems) in ideal lattices is as hard as in regular lattices."* The difficulty of these problems on regular lattices is provably NP-hard.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] There are, however, a minority of researchers who do not believe that ideal lattices share the same security properties as regular lattices.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Peikert believes that these security equivalences make the RLWE problem a good basis for future cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] He writes: *"There is a mathematical proof that the* *only* *way to break the cryptosystem (within some formal attack model) on its random instances is by being able to solve the underlying lattice problem in the* *worst case"* (emphasis in the original).
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] A major advantage that RLWE based cryptography has over the original learning with errors (LWE) based cryptography is found in the size of the public and private keys.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] RLWE keys are roughly the square root of keys in LWE.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] For 128 bits of security an RLWE cryptographic algorithm would use public keys around 7000 bits in length.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The corresponding LWE scheme would require public keys of 49 million bits for the same level of security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] On the other hand, RLWE keys are larger than the keys sizes for currently used public key algorithms like RSA and Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman which require public key sizes of 3072 bits and 256 bits, respectively, to achieve a 128-bit level of security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] From a computational standpoint, however, RLWE algorithms have been shown to be the equal of or better than existing public key systems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The fundamental idea of using LWE and Ring LWE for key exchange was proposed and filed at the University of Cincinnati in 2011 by Jintai Ding.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The basic idea comes from the associativity of matrix multiplications, and the errors are used to provide the security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] In 2014, Peikert presented a key transport scheme following the same basic idea of Ding's, where the new idea of sending additional 1 bit signal for rounding in Ding's construction is also utilized.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] An RLWE version of the classic MQV variant of a Diffie-Hellman key exchange was later published by Zhang et al.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The security of both key exchanges is directly related to the problem of finding approximate short vectors in an ideal lattice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] Homomorphic encryption is type of encryption that allows computations to be performed on encrypted data without first having to decrypt it.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] The purpose of homomorphic encryption is to allow the computations on sensitive data to occur on computing devices that should not be trusted with the data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] These computing devices are allowed to process the ciphertext which is output from a homomorphic encryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption-applied/ring-learning-with-errors] In 2011, Brakersky and Vaikuntanathan, published "Fully Homomorphic Encryption from Ring-LWE and Security for Key Dependent Messages" which builds a homomorphic encryption scheme directly on the RLWE problem.
